Figure 1: A core problem is to understand malaria transmission by mosquitoes, which requires understanding the process of exposure and infection. This diagram illustrates how the RAMP algorithms deal with the relationship.

Outline

Exposure vs. Infection

  • Malaria transmission is forced by adult mosquitoes through blood feeding.

  • We can compute thresholds for malaria elimination:

    • Threshold density of mosquitoes

    • \(R_0\) / \(R_C\)

  • We can measure exposure through the EIR, which serves as a useful measure of transmission because

    • Vectorial capacity (\(V\)) is roughly the same concept as the EIR (\(E\)). In the Ross-Macdonald model, one is derived from the other: \[E(1+s\kappa) = V\kappa\]

    • …so in the classical \(R_C = bVD \approx E (1+S\kappa) /\kappa\)

    • …and \(\kappa = f_\kappa(X(E))\) la

  • More generally, we want to know how to weigh tradeoffs through vector control:

    • Burden in relation to exposure

    • Exposure in relation to transmission

    • Transmission effect sizes (\(R_0/R_C\)) in relation to coverage

    • Coverage in relation to costs

  • …but the EIR is expensive to measure, so we need an estimate that is based on other metrics:

    • The TPR appears to be biased. It is probably reliable, but we don’t have paired estimates of the TPR and the EIR.

    • The PR is routinely measured in research settings, in DHS / MIS and there is a lot of PR data.

Models & Data

PfEIR vs. PfPR

Smith, D.L., Dushoff, J., Snow, R.W., and Hay, S.I. (2005). The entomological inoculation rate and Plasmodium falciparum infection in African children. Nature 438, 492–495.

  • Dynamic Range: for aEIR > 10, there’s almost no difference in the PR

  • Malaria Importation: for aEIR < 1, a lot of the malaria could be imported.

  • Target Effect Sizes

    • How hard is malaria elimination from aEIR = 1?

    • Malaria elimination at aEIR = 10, 100 requires roughly 10-fold, 100-fold greater reductions in vectorial capacity

Causes

  • Heterogeneous exposure

    • Exposure \(\times\) age

    • Exposure \(\times\) location

    • Exposure \(\times\) season

    • Individual-level Frailty

    • Negative binomial exposure

    • …

  • Immunity / Reduced Susceptibility

    • Chemo-protection

    • Pre-erythrocytic immunity

    • Blood stage immunity (\(\times\) age)

    • Iron Limitation

  • EIR estimates are inaccurate

Immunity

There’s an identifiability problem.

  • Filion, G.J.P., Paul, R.E.L., and Robert, V. (2006). Transmission and immunity: the importance of heterogeneity in the fight against malaria. Trends Parasitol. 22, 345–348.

  • Hoffman, S.L., Oster, C.N., Plowe, C.V., Woollett, G.R., Beier, J.C., Chulay, J.D., Wirtz, R.A., Hollingdale, M.R., and Mugambi, M. (1987). Naturally acquired antibodies to sporozoites do not prevent malaria: vaccine development implications. Science 237, 639–642.

## Vector Control {.tabset}

Example

After control with IRS, aEIR \(\approx 1\) so \(R_C \gg 40\)

  • Smith, D.L., Musiime, A.K., Maxwell, K., Lindsay, S.W., and Kiware, S. (2021). A New Test of a Theory about Old Mosquitoes.

Scaling

  • The Ross-Macdonald model predicts the wrong scaling relationships for control.
par(mfrow = c(2,1))
aEIR = 10^seq(-1, 3, length.out=100)
dEIR = aEIR/365
r=1/200
b=0.55
br = .45
k = 1/4.2
foi1 = b*dEIR
pr1 = foi1/(r+foi1)
pr2 = 1 - (1+ br*aEIR/k)^(-k)
pr3 = .084*log(aEIR) + .32
plot(aEIR, pr1, type = "l", log="x", xaxt = "n", ylab = "PR")
lines(aEIR, pr2)
lines(aEIR, pr3)
axis(1, 10^c(-1:3), c("0.1", 1, 10, 100, 1000))
plot(aEIR, pr1, type = "l", ylab = "PR", xlim = c(0.5,20))
lines(aEIR, pr2)
lines(aEIR, pr3)
